–Deceased","1122–Female":"1122–Deceased","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","about 1328":"about 1328","ABT    1330":"about 1330","1122":"1122","1330":"1330","about 1302":"about 1302","1119":"1119","1328":"1328","1306":"1306","of Tir Iarll,Gwrinydd,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Llangoed,Llys-wen,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rhys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Rees  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Rice  .","German: habitational name from a place in the Rhineland called Rees.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Andreas  ."]}]},{"name":"Meurig","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Meuric","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"\"Ddu\"","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 竇, meaning ‘hole’ in ancient Chinese: (i) adopted as a surname by Yue Zhu and Yue Long, two sons of Shao Kang, the sixth king of the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). Yue Zhu and Yue Long are said to have adopted Dou (竇) (meaning ‘hole’) as a surname because their pregnant grandmother had escaped from a rebellion through a hole in the wall before giving birth to their father, Shao Kang, who later recaptured the throne. (ii) traced back to the Dou (竇) family from the Di ethnic group and some other families from the Xianbei ethnic group in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 豆, denoting an ancient stemmed cup of bowl: (i) traced back to some inhabitants in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) adopted as the surname by the Chi Xiao Dou (赤小豆) and Dou Lu (豆盧) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 鈄, referring to a type of ancient vessel for drinking wine: said to be borne by the descendants of the Duke Kang of Qi (died 379  BC ), who was ousted from his throne in the state of Qi and sent into exile. It was said that he was forced to use the vessel Dou (鈄) to cook food during his exile, and some of his descendants inherited Dou as the surname to memorize this period."],"variants":[{"name":"Du","meanings":["‘Wealthy’."]},{"name":"Dau","meanings":["From Old Norse <i>dagr</i> ‘day’."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Meurig \"Ddu\" ap Rhys was born about 1302, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Rhys ap Meurig, was 185 and his mother, Margred ferch Hywel, was 182. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Meurig Ddu ap Rhys."},"et":{"about 1302–":"umbes 1302–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1119–Male":"1119–Surnud","1122–Female":"1122–Surnud","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","about 1328":"umbes 1328","ABT    1330":"umbes 1330","1122":"1122","1330":"1330","about 1302":"umbes 1302","1119":"1119","1328":"1328","1306":"1306","of Tir Iarll,Gwrinydd,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Llangoed,Llys-wen,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1302–":"noin 1302–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1304–Male":"1304–Kuollut","1306–Female":"1306–Kuollut","1328–Male":"1328–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1119–Male":"1119–Kuollut","1122–Female":"1122–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","about 1328":"noin 1328","ABT    1